\par
                    Abstract\par
                    A method for identifying dislocation motion in atomistic simulations is presen-\par
                    ted. While identifying static and moving dislocations within a single crystal or\par
                    a combination of such is well established, the method described here is tailored\par
                    to identify dislocation motion by correlating the displacements of individual\par
                    atoms. This facilitates the identification of dislocation motion in complex struc-\par
                    tural arrangements, and allows the specific contribution to plastic deformation,\par
                    due to dislocation motion, to be separated from that of other mechanisms. The\par
                    method is applied to test cases in crystals and grain boundaries (GBs), in which\par
                    irradiation-induced creep (IIC) was induced. It is shown that the method singles\par
                    out the moving dislocations from among the dislocation forest at GBs, thus\par
                    identifying the specific reactions driving the distortion at any given time. This\par
                    enables the study of dislocation processes in the presence of realistic obstacles,\par
                    and the study of the effects of microstructure on dislocation mobility. As an\par
                    example of such a study, the method is applied to rule out intragranular slip, and\par
                    to estimate the contribution of dislocation motion to strain, in a NC undergoing\par
                    IIC.\par
\par
                    Keywords: dislocations, molecular dynamics, graphs, nanocrystals\par
\par
1. Introduction\par
\par
Dislocation dynamics often control the plastic response of metals. These dynamics depend\par
on material properties, reactions among dislocations, and their response to ambient condi-\par
tions such as stress and strain [1]. Therefore, analyzing these dynamics lies at the core of\par
understanding various plastic processes. In most cases, however, direct observation of the\par
