\par
development of dislocation complexes is impossible [2, 3]. One alternative to direct obser-\par
vation is to run molecular dynamics (MD) simulations to study the plastic response of metals.\par
These can provide information regarding the details of the relations between atomistic arrange-\par
ments and the dislocation processes occurring in metals [4].\par
    At present, it is computationally feasible to run direct MD simulations of nanocrystals\par
(NCs) containing a few tens or hundreds of grains, each of a size of a few tens of nanometers\par
[5]. Such a simulation, with appropriate boundary conditions (periodic or simulating an\par
external load), represents a small part of a macroscopic metal. MD simulations of three-\par
dimensional periodic NC structures have been widely used to study detailed deformation\par
mechanisms under stress [6, 7]. These simulations, together with transmission electron micro-\par
scope observations, suggest that heterogeneous microstrain evolution in NCs originates in dis-\par
locations at the grain boundaries (GBs) [8]. It was shown that, during deformation, partial\par
dislocations are emitted from GBs, leading to the plastic deformation of NCs [9, 10]. Thus,\par
identifying dislocations in GBs, and especially moving dislocations, has become pivotal in the\par
study of the plasticity of NCs.\par
    The classical method used to identify dislocations is Burgers circuit construction, in which\par
paths connecting atoms in the deformed crystal, which is being inspected, are compared to\par
paths in a reference crystalline structure. Algorithms based on this method proved to be\par
extremely robust, but they require the identification, and therefore the existence, of a well-\par
defined reference local crystalline order [11\u8211?13]. As such, the effectivity of these algorithms\par
is limited at highly distorted regions, and specifically near GBs and other large-scale defects.\par
    Variation of the underlying structure of the crystal is accounted for in the dislocation extrac-\par
tion algorithm (DXA) [13, 14]. This method can identify dislocations even in large complexes\par
and near GBs, and was used to identify large static distributions of dislocations [13\u8211?17]. In\par
some cases, however, the plastic activity of a metal is determined by the motion of only a small\par
number of these dislocations. In such cases, following the changes in the static distribution of\par
all dislocations may be computationally prohibitive, and does not provide enough information\par
to understand the processes driving the plastic activity. This is exacerbated by the fact that the\par
accuracy of tracking all the dislocations in a complex environment is limited. In these cases, to\par
study plastic activity, it is imperative to single out the dislocations driving it, i.e. those which\par
are in motion.\par
    In this paper, we describe a method to identify dislocations that have moved in a crystal.\par
This method utilizes the highly-correlated displacements of individual atoms characterizing\par
dislocation motion. The method, which we call the common motion grouping (CMG) method,\par
singles out moving dislocations, does not assume any underlying crystal structure, and is not\par
computationally intensive. It is, therefore, well adapted to the study of plasticity driven by the\par
generation of dislocations at GBs.\par
\par
\par
2. Description of the CMG method\par
\par
The CMG algorithm is based on identifying the correlation of the displacements of individual\par
atoms between consecutive time frames. This is done in two steps:\par
   First, atoms whose displacement, relative to their local environment, exceeds rmin are identi-\par
fied. This minimal value is determined to eliminate atoms whose displacement is due to normal\par
thermal Gaussian motion (see appendix A).\par
   Next, the non-thermally displaced atoms are organized as nodes of a binary graph. An edge\par
connects every two atoms that moved in a correlated manner, which is defined as fulfilling two\par
conditions:\par
\par
