\par
\par
\par
 1. The two atoms are within distance d of each other, where the value of d is between the\par
    nearest-neighbor and the next-nearest-neighbor distances in the lattice (see appendix A).\par
 2. The cosine of the angle between their relative displacements has an absolute value that is\par
    greater than cos \u952?max , meaning that their displacements were directionally correlated. For\par
    details of how cos \u952?max is determined, see appendix A.\par
\par
    The atoms are grouped into connected components, i.e. groups of atoms that are all con-\par
nected, either directly or via other connected nodes [18].\par
    Nonthermal atomic motion can be caused by defects other than dislocations, but will not, in\par
general, involve the correlated motion of several atoms in the same direction. Thus, to differen-\par
tiate between moving dislocations and atomic motion caused by other defects, only groups that\par
consist of at least N atoms (see appendix A) that moved in a correlated manner are identified\par
as loci of valid moving dislocations.\par
\par
\par
3. Validation\par
\par
 To validate the CMG algorithm presented in section 2, we examine its performance when\par
 applied to the results of the MD simulations of two geometrically simple cases. In both cases,\par
 simulations of single fcc Cu grains were performed using LAMMPS [19], and employing the\par
 widely-used embedded atom method (EAM) potential [20]. In each simulation, two perfect\par
 dislocations were introduced. The displacements of atoms due to the motion of these disloca-\par
 tions were then analyzed using the CMG method, and were shown to be consistent with the\par
 results of the commonly-used DXA algorithm [14].\par
    In reference simulation A, an fcc lattice was created with dimensions Lx = 358 \u197?,\par
 Ly = 501 \u197?, and Lz = 27 \u197?, oriented along the axes shown in figure 1, and with periodic\par
 boundaries. Two straight edge dislocations with opposite Burgers vectors parallel to the x axis,\par
