4. Implementations and performance\par
\par
With the CMG method validated using the reference simulations of section 3, we examine its\par
performance in a complex realistic configuration of GBs of a NC undergoing creep, for which\par
it is primarily intended. A cubic NC sample of fcc Cu, 224 \u197? long and composed of seventeen\par
grains, was produced using the method of Voronoi tessellation [25]. GBs were then modified\par
to contain V atoms by switching some of the Cu atoms, using a combined grand canonical\par
Monte-Carlo simulation and MD relaxation, as implemented in LAMMPS [26]. By setting an\par
effective reservoir temperature of 300 K and a chemical potential of 2.8 eV, a metastable state\par
with a solute concentration of 0.9% was created. Due to the high miscibility, V atoms were\par
inserted only at GBs, and at this concentration they stabilized the crystal against spontaneous\par
grain growth. The interactions between atoms was calculated using the EAM potential of [27].\par
    To demonstrate the utility of the method, irradiation-induced creep (IIC) was induced by\par
switching Cu atoms at the GBs and at the monolayers adjacent to them [28], i.e. by removing\par
each atom to create a vacancy and reinserting it as an interstitial atom. The CMG method is\par
particularly useful in such a case, because it differentiates between displacements caused by\par
dislocation motion and those due to the irradiation-induced point-defect flux. Seventy atoms\par
were removed and reinserted at a time, after which the sample was allowed to relax for 80 ps.\par
(The insertion of 140 defects at a time was possible because the relaxation process was found\par
to be local.) This was repeated for 1300 cycles to bring the sample to second-stage creep, and\par
then for another 500 cycles, during which measurements were taken. Throughout this process,\par
the sample was subjected to a constant compressive stress of 4 kbar in the [001] direction (z\par
axis) of the simulation box, using the LAMMPS NPT command.\par
