allows direct study of the dislocation dynamics in the NC. Furthermore, as most of the moving\par
dislocations were embedded within the highly distorted regions of the GBs, they were identi-\par
fied only by the CMG method and not by the DXA, because the DXA relies on a well-defined\par
local crystalline structure. The motion of these dislocations can be studied in connection with\par
the yield-stress response of the sample in question.\par
    As an example of such an analysis, the moving dislocations detected in the 500 irradiation\par
cycles of second-stage creep were examined. Each moving dislocation displaced a group of\par
atoms. The greatest of these displacements, for each moving dislocation, was saved. In addi-\par
tion, the direction of each dislocation was estimated by finding the direction of the vector con-\par
necting the two atoms in the group that were farthest apart. The angles between the dislocation\par
lines and the displacement direction, for the moving dislocations detected by the CMG method\par
at the end of all 500 cycles, were collected into a histogram, shown in figure 8. It is seen that\par
these angles are mostly less than 30\u9702? . This is characteristic of dislocations with a dominant\par
screw-type component (see figure 5), including pure and dissociated screw dislocations.\par
    Additionally, the locations of the moving dislocations in the 500 cycles of second-stage\par
creep were analyzed. All 32 183 moving dislocations, with no exception, were found to be\par
within or adjacent to GBs, rather than moving across a grain. We conclude that creep in the\par
simulated sample was affected by GB mobility, with no contribution of intragranular disloca-\par
tion activity. This finding is in line with previous studies of NC Cu which suggested, based on\par
measured dislocation densities within grains, that GB mobility is the dominant mechanism of\par
plastic deformation when the grains are smaller than \u8764?10 nm [10, 31\u8211?35].\par
