5. Limitations\par
\par
As shown in the previous sections, the CMG method can be used to detect moving disloca-\par
tions both within grains and at GBs. Its ability to single out the moving dislocations at GBs is\par
significant, because it allows the analysis of NC plasticity near GBs. The method works, fur-\par
thermore, without assuming an underlying crystal structure, thus making it flexible and robust.\par
In this section we list and discuss a few of the limitations of the CMG method. Some of these\par
limitations are inherent, and others remain because the method is still in development.\par
    Slow-moving dislocations. By design, the CMG method only detects moving dislocations.\par
If a dislocation moves slowly, the displacement of atoms between two close time frames might\par
be less than the threshold of detection. The sampling rate of the CMG method must correspond,\par
therefore, to the typical speed of dislocations in the system under inspection.\par
    Dislocation forests. As seen in reference simulation B of section 3 (in which a dissociated\par
screw dislocation was identified as one screw dislocation rather than two partials), the CMG\par
method identifies the motion of proximate dislocations as that of one complex dislocation. This\par
is an inherent feature of the method since it analyzes the displacements of groups of atoms.\par
If the motion of a group of atoms is correlated, they will all belong to the same connected\par
component of the CMG graph. Conversely, if at least N atoms are affected by one dislocation\par
and not others, they will belong to a separate connected component, and will thus be identified\par
as a separate dislocation.\par
    Burgers vector. The CMG method represents atoms as nodes of a binary graph, connected by\par
edges if they are nearby and move in the same (or opposite) direction. If the path on the graph\par
between two atoms is long, their direction of motion might be very different, even though\par
they belong to the same dislocation, see figure 5. The magnitudes of the displacements of\par
atoms, too, vary within one dislocation. Therefore, the detection of a dislocation does not\par
automatically yield its Burgers vector, as is the case, for example, in the DXA. Such analysis\par
is in fact possible, but requires a more detailed study of the specific displacement vectors, and\par
is left for future extension.\par
    Dislocation lines. The CMG method identifies groups of atoms whose positions shift due\par
to moving dislocations, rather than tracing the dislocation lines themselves. In other words,\par
the method will not pinpoint the regions of the crystal lattice around which Burgers circuits\par
\par
