\par
\par
\par
fail to close. This can be an advantage when studying the effect of multiple dislocations on\par
the lattice and grain structure of a sample, but might be a disadvantage when studying the\par
velocities of isolated dislocations [28, 36\u8211?38]. The method can be developed to support such\par
studies by improving the accuracy of the identification of the edges of the areas swept by\par
the moving dislocations and incorporating improved static structure criteria. In the current\par
implementation, the velocity of a dislocation might be estimated by calculating the rate of\par
propagation of the center of mass of the atoms that are shifted by its motion.\par
    Misidentification of deformations as dislocations. In metastable scenarios with high ener-\par
gies, the ensuing dynamics may involve correlated motion of chunks of matter, which is not\par
driven by the motion of dislocations. The CMG method does not differentiate between chunks\par
of matter moving together and moving dislocations. This type of scenario can include the ini-\par
tial steps of some simulations, in which the system has not yet relaxed into a low-energy state,\par
and situations in which failure is incipient.\par
\par
\par
6. Conclusions\par
\par
Detailed local study of plasticity in NCs and other structures, containing large populations\par
of defects and dislocations, requires the identification of a small number of moving disloca-\par
tions in complex environments. The CMG method, introduced here, facilitates such studies by\par
identifying correlated displacements due to moving dislocations. This is done by comparing\par
atomic positions at consecutive time frames. The method was applied to quantify and char-\par
acterize displacements due to moving dislocations in a NC undergoing creep, and to estimate\par
the contribution of these dislocations to the NC strain. Using this method, it was shown that\par
all dislocation activity was identified within the GB, with no significant contribution due to\par
intragranular activity.\par
    Although the method now compares two specific time frames, it can be extended to examine\par
multiple time steps. This will allow the calculation of properties such as dislocation drag and\par
velocity, and better filtering of specific dislocation mechanisms. Also, tools can be developed\par
to determine the Burgers vectors of the detected dislocations, to facilitate the study of the types\par
of dislocations that drive plasticity in various settings.\par
    In addition to the study of plasticity in NCs, the CMG method can be used in other settings\par
in conjunction with static structural methods, to discern among dislocations that moved and\par
those that remained stationary. This can include situations in which sessile dislocations become\par
mobile, as a result of reactions induced by stress or radiation. The identification of the onset\par
of dislocation-based displacements, in such settings, can provide information regarding the\par
activation energies and volumes of different types of yield mechanisms.\par
