Appendix A. Determining the parameters of the algorithm\par
\par
Table 1 lists the parameters used in the current implementation of the CMG algorithm, and\par
their values in the simulations presented in this manuscript (except in the simulation described\par
in appendix B). In this appendix, we detail how these values were derived.\par
    rmin is used to identify atoms that changed their position between two time frames under\par
comparison. Its value was calculated using the atomic positions at ti = 106.08 ns and tf =\par
106.16 ns from the beginning of the GB simulation of section 4. The magnitudes of the atomic\par
displacements between these time frames were arranged in a histogram and fitted to a \u967? dis-\par
tribution with three degrees of freedom, see figure 10, under the assumption that thermal dis-\par
placements lead to a normal distribution in each spatial dimension. Thus, rmin = 0.7 \u197?, where\par
the displacements noticeably diverge from the \u967?3 distribution, was chosen as the threshold of\par
non-Gaussian motion.\par
    Although the value of rmin can be determined separately for every simulated sample (at\par
every point of time), its calculation yields similar values for a given material and temperature.\par
Thus, the value yielded by the calculation above was used in all the simulations described in\par
this paper, except in that of appendix B.\par
    The next parameter in the CMG algorithm, d, is used to determine the correlation length of\par
atoms moving due to one dislocation. We expect dislocations to affect contiguous groups of\par
atoms, at adjacent positions along the crystal lattice. Therefore, to determine d, we examine a\par
histogram of distances among pairs of atoms in the simulated NC at tf = 106.16 ps, produced\par
by Ovito\u8217?s pair distribution function [23]. d is any value between the two leftmost peaks of\par
the histogram. In our case, as shown in figure 11, it can be d = 3 \u197?. (Once again, choosing a\par
different time frame from the NC simulation, or from the reference simulations, yields similar\par
results.) In general, in fairly ordered crystals, d should have a value between the distances\par
among nearest and next-nearest neighbors.\par
    To estimate the next parameter, cos \u952?max , we consider that two atoms, displaced by the pas-\par
sage of a moving dislocation, should be displaced in the same direction. Typically, for the\par
fcc crystals simulated in this work, the magnitude   \u8730? of this displacement will be equal to the\par
Burgers vector of a partial dislocation, i.e. b = a/ 6 = 1.48 \u197?, where a is the lattice constant\par
in Cu. Thermal motion, however, can cause the directions of the displacements to diverge. This\par
will be most pronounced when the thermal motions of the atoms are in opposite directions,\par
perpendicular to the motion due to the passage of the moving dislocation. We estimated the\par
maximum displacement of thermal motion as rmin , so the maximum angle between the direc-\par
tions of motion of two atoms will be \u952?max = arctan(rmin /b). Therefore, the minimum cosine\par
of the angle between the displacement vectors will be cos \u952?max = 0.9.\par
    The reasoning applied to estimate cos \u952?max assumes an fcc lattice structure with fairly con-\par
sistent atomic spacing, and where partial Shockley dislocations are common. Similar reasoning\par
can be developed in other settings, too, as long as interatomic distances are greater than the\par
typical thermal displacement of atoms. Along these lines, the CMG method may be extended\par
to highly complex systems such as high-entropy alloys.\par
    The last parameter of the CMG algorithm is N, the minimum amount of moving atoms that\par
indicates the passage of a moving dislocation. A large value for this parameter would lead to the\par
misdetection of small moving dislocations. A small value would lead to the false identification\par
of moving point defects as moving dislocations, since there is a motion of atoms around point\par
defects due to relaxation. Under the assumption that not all of the nearest neighbors around a\par
point defect will move in a common direction, we chose N = 12 as the optimal value for the\par
fcc lattices in this work.\par
