positions at ti = 11 ps and tf = 20 ps from the beginning of the simulation. As in section 3,\par
these time frames were chosen due to the visual clarity of the results of the DXA and the CMG\par
method.\par
    The CMG method singles out atoms that have shifted by more than rmin between time\par
frames, to examine if their motion is due to moving dislocations. rmin itself is determined stat-\par
istically per sample. As the temperature increases, thus widening the \u967?3 distribution of the\par
thermal motion of atoms, the concept of singling out atoms by comparing two frames will\par
become less effective. It can be expected to break down when there is a statistically significant\par
likelihood for atoms to be shifted by a magnitude greater than that of the Burgers vector of\par
the dislocations of interest. We see, however, that at 700 K in the scenarios in this study, this\par
concept continues to be effective. At even higher temperatures, the algorithm might be mod-\par
ified by inspecting the mean coordinates of the atoms of the sample over the time period of\par
interest, thus reducing the effect of Brownian motion on the CMG method.\par
